{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614868"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:49:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:49:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16378"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16378"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.08,0.33,0.28,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9069"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65820"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9069","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9069"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16378"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51265"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9924"},{"type":"tags","id":"9925"},{"type":"tags","id":"10350"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21560"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21561"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65820","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65820"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe respiratory pattern is controlled by several interconnected regions in the brainstem that form the respiratory control centre.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following brainstem regions is primarily responsible for generating the basic respiratory rhythm?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pneumotaxic centre","B\u00f6tzinger complex","Pre-B\u00f6tzinger complex","Dorsal respiratory group","Apneustic centre"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epre-B\u00f6tzinger complex\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary respiratory rhythm generator in the brainstem, located in the ventral respiratory group of the medulla, and sometimes referred to as the central pattern generator. It contains pacemaker-like neurons that produce rhythmic bursts of activity driving inspiration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other regions, all located within the brainstem, have different roles:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Epneumotaxic centre\u003C/strong\u003E in the pons helps regulate respiratory rate and provides inhibitory input to limit inspiration\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003EB\u00f6tzinger complex\u003C/strong\u003E contains inhibitory neurons that help coordinate the transition between inspiration and expiration\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edorsal respiratory group\u003C/strong\u003E of the medulla contains premotor neurons that drive inspiratory muscles\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eapneustic centre\u003C/strong\u003E in the pons promotes prolonged inspiration when uninhibited\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese regions work together as an integrated circuit to produce and modify the breathing rate and volume based on physiological needs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The pre-B\u00f6tzinger complex generates the basic rhythm for breathing by producing inspiratory bursts.","Multiple brainstem nuclei work together to control breathing patterns, including the B\u00f6tzinger complex, pre-B\u00f6tzinger complex, and dorsal respiratory group.","The pneumotaxic centre helps regulate respiratory rate and depth by providing inhibitory input to the respiratory rhythm generator."],"references":["Mu\u00f1oz-Ortiz J, Mu\u00f1oz-Ortiz E, L\u00f3pez-Meraz ML, Beltran-Parrazal L, Morgado-Valle C. Pre-B\u00f6tzinger complex: Generation and modulation of respiratory rhythm. Neurologia (Engl Ed). 2019 Sep;34(7):461-468. English, Spanish. doi: 10.1016/j.nrl.2016.05.011. Epub 2016 Jul 18. PMID: 27443242.","Smith JC, Ellenberger HH, Ballanyi K, Richter DW, Feldman JL. Pre-B\u00f6tzinger complex: a brainstem region that may generate respiratory rhythm in mammals. Science. 1991 Nov 1;254(5032):726-9. doi: 10.1126/science.1683005. PMID: 1683005; PMCID: PMC3209964.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51265"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16378"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51265"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-27T08:59:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T08:59:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9069"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65820"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":nu